# API Contract — One Shape. Every Route. Always.

## The standard response type

Copy this into your project and use it everywhere. No custom shapes per route.

```typescript
type ApiResponse<T = null> = 
  | { success: true; data: T }
  | { success: false; error: string; code: string }

// Usage in a route
return Response.json({ success: true, data: user } satisfies ApiResponse<User>)
return Response.json({ success: false, error: "Not found", code: "USER_NOT_FOUND" } satisfies ApiResponse, { status: 404 })
```

---

## HTTP status code rules — memorise these

| Status | When to use |
|---|---|
| 200 | Success — returning data |
| 201 | Success — something was created |
| 400 | Bad input — validation failed, missing fields |
| 401 | Not logged in |
| 403 | Logged in but not allowed to do this |
| 404 | Resource does not exist |
| 409 | Conflict — duplicate, already exists |
| 429 | Rate limited |
| 500 | Server error — something you did not expect |

Never return 200 with `success: false` inside the body.
Never return 500 for something the user caused.
Never return 400 for something the server caused.

---

## Before building any new endpoint

State this out loud before writing code:

```
ENDPOINT BRIEF
──────────────
Route: [METHOD /api/path]
Auth required: YES / NO
Rate limited: YES / NO
Success response: [the data shape inside ApiResponse<T>]
Possible error codes: [list every MACHINE_READABLE_CODE this route can return]
```

---

## Audit existing routes — run this check

Go through every file in `/app/api` or `/pages/api` and check:

- [ ] Every route returns `ApiResponse<T>` shape — no custom shapes
- [ ] No route returns `{ message: string }` alone — that is not the standard
- [ ] No route returns `{ data: null, error: null }` ambiguity
- [ ] Every route uses the correct HTTP status code for its response
- [ ] Every error response has a `code` field in SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE
- [ ] No route swallows errors silently and returns 200 when it should return 500
- [ ] Auth check happens at the top of every protected route — not halfway through
- [ ] No route returns a different shape depending on a condition

---

## Error code naming convention

Error codes are SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE and describe what went wrong — not where it went wrong.

```
GOOD: USER_NOT_FOUND, INVALID_EMAIL, SESSION_EXPIRED, PLAN_LIMIT_REACHED
BAD:  ERROR_404, FAILED, SOMETHING_WRONG, DB_ERROR
```

---

## The rule in one line

One type. One shape. Every route. If an existing route breaks this — fix it before adding a new one.
